[5
Date: Friday, October 19, 2001 10:48 AM
From: George M Strain <strain@lsu.edu>

Subject: Ames strain
I got this today from the Iowa State Alumni Assn:
** ISU NEWS FLASH - October 19, 2001**
A service to members of the Iowa State University Alumni Association.
DEBUNKING THE AMES ANTHRAX STORY
The false story spread as fast as a flu bug in a daycare center: The FBI
had traced the origin of the anthrax that killed a Florida man to a bacteria
that had been manufactured and harvested in a laboratory in Ames, Iowa.
Eighty phone calls and seven TV interviews later, ISU Veterinary Medicine
faculty finally got the word out: Wrong!
Here's the story: A strain, which originated from an Iowa cow, was
identified in 1980 at the National Veterinary Services Laboratory and was
shipped for further research to the US Army Medical Research Lab in
Frederick, Md., where it was named the "Ames strain." ISU's Veterinary
Medicine College did not conduct research on the strain, nor did they
maintain the culture.
The story got muddled a bit, because of the presence of another strain of
anthrax, which had been dried, preserved, and stored at the college for
historic reasons. Isolated in 1925 and sealed in 1928, the bacteria were part
of a culture created by ISU veterinary medicine professor, Ival A. Merchant.
Custody of the cultures was handed down through the generations of ISU
microbiologists who followed, with a goal of opening the sealed tubes for
testing in the year 2028, 100 years after their sealing.
But the specimens weren't really needed for teaching or research, and the
FBI and Centers for Disease Control had no interest in the old samples.
Following a day of around-the-clock guarding by the Iowa highway patrol,
college administrators decided to destroy the historic anthrax. On 12 Oct
[2001,
the specimens were burned, in the presence of a patrol officer.
--
George M. Strain
Associate Vice Chancellor
Office of Research & Graduate Studies
Louisiana State University
240 Thomas Boyd Hall
Baton Rouge, LA 70803
<strain@lsu.edu>
[It would now be interesting to see which "Ames" was involved. - Mod.MHJ
